  <h1>On Speed</h1>
  <p><em>Abe Levin Â· January 18, 2026</em></p>

  <p>Something subtle has changed in the environment.</p>

  <p>
    Work now returns faster than it used to. Questions reappear before the last
    one has finished settling. Clarity is requested again while the system is
    still integrating the previous cycle. Nothing dramatic happens. There is no
    obvious overload. Tasks continue to complete. Decisions continue to land.
  </p>

  <p>And yet, capacity thins.</p>

  <p>
    This strain doesn't resemble the burnout people are used to recognizing.
    There is no collapse, no emotional volatility, no loss of function. Most
    people experiencing it are competent, regulated, and engaged. They are doing
    well by any external measure. What's missing isn't discipline or resilience.
    What's missing is time for the system to finish restoring itself before it is
    pulled back into engagement.
  </p>

  <p>Speed has removed friction.</p>

  <p>
    In earlier environments, pauses were enforced. Waiting was built into
    process. Delays created natural boundaries between cycles of attention,
    decision, and action. Those boundaries allowed judgment to widen again,
    uncertainty to be held without pressure, and internal balance to
    re-stabilize before the next demand arrived.
  </p>

  <p>That friction is no longer reliable.</p>

  <p>
    When engagement recurs too quickly, the system compensates. Movement
    continues, but now narrowing what it carries. Force replaces order. Urgency
    substitutes for sequence. Meaning is asked for before clarity has formed.
    Responsibility settles before agency is fully available. None of this feels
    wrong in the moment. It feels necessary.
  </p>

  <p>Because nothing breaks, the signal stays quiet.</p>

  <p>
    This is why the exhaustion arrives without a clear cause. The system is
    adapting to an environment that no longer enforces completion. Burnout here
    is not a personal limit being reached. It is settling being skipped.
  </p>

  <p>
    Nothing about this requires rejecting new tools or slowing work for its own
    sake. The strain doesn't come from lack of intelligence, over ambition, or
    intensity. It comes from cycles that never quite finish. When restoration is
    deferred repeatedly, capacity erodes even in systems that were previously
    stable.
  </p>

  <p>Nothing is broken.</p>

  <p>Order was simply asked to carry more speed than it could hold.</p>
</BaseLayout>
